        <p>
        <em><me>Learning Point</me></em>
        </p>

        <p>
            Fraction <m>\frac{a}{b}</m> can be expressed as a ratio a:b, ie
        </p>
        <p>
            To express a fraction we introduce <em>colons</em> to separate the numerator and the denominator of the fraction, ie
        </p>
        <p>
            <me>\frac{3}{8} = 3:8</me>            
        </p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The number of boys in a class of <m>50</m> learners is <m>30</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Find the number of girls.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Express the number of boys as a fraction to the number of girls.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Find the ratio of the number of boys to the number of girls.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>

            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The number of girls in the class is given as;
                                <me>\text{Total number of learners of a class} \minus \text{Number of boys in the class} </me>                                 
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <me>50 - 30 = 20 \text{girls present in class.}</me>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                To express the of boys to girls as fraction, we have to divide the number of boys to that of girls in the class
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Previously, we had boys = <m>30</m> and girls = <m>20</m>.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <me>\text{Boys as a fractions} = \frac{30}{20}</me>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <me>= \frac{3}{2}</me>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Expressing fractions to ratios we introduce <em>colons</em> instead of the fraction bar.
                            </p>   
                            <p>
                                <me>\text{Ratio of boys to girls} = 3:2</me>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A solution contains <m>20</m> grams of salt and <m>100</m> millilitres of water. Find the ratio of salt to water.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    To find the ratio of salt to water, we have to divide the amount of salt by the amount of water.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Expressing fractions to ratios we introduce <em>colons</em>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <me>\text{Fraction of salt to water} = \frac{20}{100}</me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <me>= \frac{1}{5}</me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefore, the ratio of salt to water is <me>\text{Ratio of salt to water} = 1:5</me>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A solution consists of <m>\frac{3}{5}</m> of liquid A and the rest is liquid B.
                </p>

                <p>
                     <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Express the liquid A as a fraction to liquid B in the mixture.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Find the ratio A:B.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>

            <solution>

                <p>
                    To find the amount in solution B we substrat the amount of liquid A from the total amount of the solution.
                </p>

                <p>
                    The total solution adds up to <m>1</m>.
                </p>

                <p>
                    Therefore, the amount of liquid B is <m>1 - \frac{3}{5} = \frac{2}{5}</m>.
                </p>

                <p>
                    To express the liquid A as a fraction to liquid B, we have to divide the amount of liquid A by the amount of liquid B.
                </p>

                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Now lets divide the amount of liquid A by the amount of liquid B.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <me>\frac{Liquid A}{Liquid B} = \frac{\frac{3}{5}}{\frac{2}{5}}</me>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            To solve for the fraction we invert the divisor and multiply.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <me>= \frac{3}{5} \times \frac{5}{2}</me>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Therefore, the amount of liquid A as a fraction to liquid B is;
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <me>\text{Liquid A as a fraction} = \frac{3}{2}</me>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Expressing fractions to ratios we introduce <em>colons</em> to separate the numerator and the denominator of the fraction.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <me>\text{Ratio A:B} = 3:2</me>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                
            </solution>
        </example>
    </subsubsection>
    
